In rec.antiques, Mark Nolan wrote:

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;The good news; antiques are free of duty and VAT

"/> Mark, just one point, they are not FREE of VAT they are Zero rated, and
that may not always be the case, they are rated not exempt.

FWIW and slightly off the topic. In the UK homemakers, a 100 years old
object and/or works of art (less than 100 years old) can be sold under
the VAT scope of the special scheme. That means, if the buyer is not
claiming VAT then the goods can be sold zero rated by the seller under
&quot;special scheme for antiques and works of art&quot;, and the registered VAT
seller will only pay VAT at 17.5% on his profit to the VAT office,
provided, he (the seller) bought the object in, at special scheme in the
first place. If he, OTHO, bought the goods in, at plus VAT, then he must
sell the goods out at plus VAT and pay the VAT office 17.5% on the FULL
selling price. Auction houses in the UK operate under special scheme.
That's why we only pay VAT on the auctioneers commission fees, which of
course he the auctioneer returns to the VAT office.

If the original poster is a private, and non-registered for VAT, then he
will have to import the objects as private use. His level of reoccurring
and frequency activity may well (or may well not) catch the eye of the
VAT people.

A friend of mine has just received a bill from the VAT squad for £18000
over several containers he brought in as private import and use, the VAT
people are not disputing the fact, and as such they don't have to PROVE
the case, he has to DISPROVE the case, if he can't then it's pay up
time. Extreme? yes, but a warning.

Ronnie
