&gt;nodded politely). But I still don't understand the reference. What
&gt;does &quot;value added&quot; mean?

"/> Marshall, it is simply an indirect tax, much like a purchase tax (sales
tax). Currently there are two rates, Zero rate and a rate of 17.5%, some
good are exempt, fewer exempts these days. It's an input and output tax.
The tax is collected by VAT registered businesses and services from the
general public and non-registered traders, the VAT rate being added to
the value of the goods or service sold. The different between the input
and output tax by the registered businesses is returned to the VAT office
or refunded by the VAT office, whatever the case, via a quarterly VAT
return. If a business (full time or part-time) exceeds a set threshold
on their turnover (I think at the moment £12500 in any one quarter of
£50000 in a year) they must register for VAT by law. It is also voluntary
and if the business is below the threshold they still can enter the VAT
scheme, so as to claim VAT refunds on business goods and expenses.

In the UK, value-added tax (VAT) raises about half as much as the
personal income tax, and together excise duties and VAT raise about
one-third of total tax revenue. We are UNPAID tax collectors for the
government. I believe in the States it's the other way around, purchase
tax (sales tax) is relatively unimportant and the main bulk of revenue
coming from direct tax?

Any the wiser? :)

Ronnie
