Ronnie, here it's almost the same except for which government gets the
money. &lt;g&gt;

States, counties and cities set a sales tax rate. If you're buying for
resale, you show them your Tax Number and they don't charge you tax.
Otherwise, the dealer charges you tax, then passes it on to the state
who figures out which county and city get how much.

Out-of-state sales are also (currently) tax exempt, although most states
have a Use Tax which the purchaser of out-of-state goods is supposed to
send in to the state. Most do not, but large companies who get audited
could find themselves owing the state a bundle in tax for all their mail
order office supplies and such.

Now, WHAT is taxable, depends on the state. In NJ, they don't tax the
necessities of life (food, clothing, medicine) or services (doctors,
lawyers); in NM, everything is taxable; in FL, service isn't nor is food
unless it's things like soda. In NJ, the &quot;necessities&quot; rule is a little
absurd... seeds to grow veggies isn't, but seeds to grow flowers is,
while bath soap is, flea soap (medicine) for your dog isn't.

NJ also had the strangest &quot;blue laws&quot; on the books: you couldn't buy a
toaster on a Sunday, but you could buy a refrigerator. You could buy
clothes, but not the fabric to sew your own. The end result is that most
stores used to close on Sundays, but eventually the stores lost money to
nearby states (especially during Christmas buying season), and most of
the laws were repealed (although I think you can still only buy beer and
wine, but not liquor on Sundays unless you drink it in the bar).

Have fun, Michele
