<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;Does this mean that they collect VAT every time a piece changes hands?

"/> More or less yes. BUT it's an INPUT and OUTPUT tax for a registered
business, must bear that in mind. If you are not registered or are a Joe
Public then in most cases you cannot reclaim the VAT. There are some
exceptions to this, which I will not go into.

Take a manufacture, he sells his product to the wholesaler at XXX plus
VAT. The wholesaler sells to a retailer at XXX (plus their profit) plus
VAT. The retailer sells to Joe Public at XXX (plus his profit) plus VAT.

The manufacture, wholesaler and retailer can offset the input VAT they
were charged when they bought the goods in, against the output VAT they
added when they sold, so really the only one actually paying VAT is Joe
Public. The businesses are collecting tax from Joe Public. The
manufacture would of course be entitled to offset the VAT charged on his
raw materials used in the manufacture of the product against his output
tax to the wholesaler, or who ever he sells to. Services are also subject
to VAT. Businesses (registered for VAT) can reclaim all VAT on anything
against their business either capital expenditure or business expenses.
In essence, it's an end user or consumer tax paid at the end of the line,
the difference between input and output.

This is a rather simplified version but there are a number of VAT schemes
contained within the VAT scope for special trades and businesses.
Antiques is one these which I explained the last time, it has it's own
special scheme, as does other second-hand markets. The are certain items
and services that can be Zero rated (0%) and certain items and services
that are exempt (free from the VAT scheme) although government prefer to
Zero rate rather than apply exemptions, for obvious reasons.

It is not really a complicated system, it may sound a bit complex on
paper but is easy worked in practice. However, it's bloody unfair.
Originally, antiques were meant to have the full VAT added to the selling
price, this was fought by a number of antique trade associations and was
replaced with the special scheme for antiques. In which the **dealer**
pay VAT on his profit, the same as the auctions. Talk recently was that
the EU wished to add VAT to the hammer price at auction, personally I
think that is a bloody good idea, for obvious reasons, if you have
followed my above explanation of the VAT scheme.;&gt;

